
[1]pretext

   PRETEXT', n. [L. proetextus.] Pretense; false appearance; ostensible
   reason or motive assigned or assumed as a color or cover for the real
   reason or motive. He gave plausible reasons for this conduct, but these
   were only a pretext to conceal his real motives.

   He made pretext that I should only go

   And help convey his freight; but thought not so.

   They suck the blood of those they depend on, under a pretext of service
   and kindness.
